===Etymology 1===
From {{inh|en|enm|abiect||outcast, wretched}}, from {{der|en|la|abiectus}}, past participle of {{m|la|abiciō||to throw away, cast off, to reject}}, from {{prefix|la|ab|t1=away|iaciō|t2=to throw|nocat=yes}}<ref>{{R:CDOE|page=3}}</ref>.

====Adjective====
{{en-adj|er|more}}

# {{lb|en|obsolete}} Rejected; cast aside. {{defdate|Attested from around (1350 to 1470) until the early 17<sup>th</sup> century.}}<ref name=SOED>{{R:SOED5|page=5}}</ref>
# Sunk to or existing in a low condition, state, or position. {{defdate|First attested from around (1350 to 1470).}}<ref name=SOED/>
#* {{quote-book|en|passage=So thick bestrown '''abject''' and lost lay these, covering the flood.|author={{w|John Milton}}|title={{w|Paradise Lost}}|year=1667}}
# Cast down in spirit or hope; [[degraded]]; [[servile]]; [[grovelling]]; [[despicable]]; lacking courage; offered in a [[humble]] and often [[ingratiating]] spirit. {{defdate|First attested from around (1350 to 1470).}}<ref name=SOED/>
#* {{quote-book|en|1710|{{w|Joseph Addison}}|Whig Examiner|passage=Honest men, who tell their sovereigns what they expect from them, and what obedience they shall be always ready to pay them, are not upon an equal foot with such base and '''abject''' flatterers;|issue=5}}
#* {{quote-book|en|passage=Lord Howard of Escrick accused Ayloffe of proposing to assassinate the Duke of York; but Lord Howard was an '''abject''' liar;|author={{w|Thomas Babington Macaulay}}|title=The History of England from the Accession of James the Second|year=1848}}
#* {{RQ:Shakespeare Taming of the Shrew|I|ii|passage=And banish hence these '''abject''', lowly dreams.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|passage=He sat obediently with that tentative and '''abject''' eagerness of a man who has but one pleasure left and whom the world can reach only through one sense, for he was both blind and deaf.|year=1931|author=Faulkner|title=Sanctuary|section=ii}}
# Showing utter [[hopelessness]], [[helplessness]]; showing resignation; [[wretched]]. {{defdate|First attested from around (1350 to 1470).}}<ref name=SOED/>
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1927|title=From the Dark Tower|author=Countee Cullen|passage=We shall not always plant while others reap \ The golden [[increment]] of bursting fruit, \ Not always [[countenance]], '''abject''' and mute \ That lesser men should [[hold cheap|hold their brothers cheap]];}}

